%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np
import cv2
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from skimage.morphology import *
#from skimage.morphology import watershed as skwater

def ShowImage(title,img,ctype):
  plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
  if ctype=='bgr':
    b,g,r = cv2.split(img)       # get b,g,r
    rgb_img = cv2.merge([r,g,b])     # switch it to rgb
    plt.imshow(rgb_img)
  elif ctype=='hsv':
    rgb = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_HSV2RGB)
    plt.imshow(rgb)
  elif ctype=='gray':
    plt.imshow(img,cmap='gray')
  elif ctype=='rgb':
    plt.imshow(img)
  else:
    raise Exception("Unknown colour type")
  plt.axis('off')
  plt.title(title)
  plt.show()

In [ ]:
import numpy as np

# Assuming thresh is the thresholded image obtained using Otsu's method
# Get the connected components in the thresholded image
ret, markers = cv2.connectedComponents(thresh)

# Get the area taken by each component. Ignore label 0 since this is the background.
marker_area = [np.sum(markers==m) for m in range(1, np.max(markers)+1)]  # Start from 1 to skip background
# Get label of largest component by area
largest_component = np.argmax(marker_area) + 1  # Add 1 since we started labeling from 1
# Get pixels which correspond to the brain
brain_mask = markers == largest_component

# Convert gray_uint16 to uint8 for display purposes
gray_uint8 = cv2.convertScaleAbs(gray_uint16)

brain_out = cv2.cvtColor(gray_uint8, cv2.COLOR_GRAY2RGB)
# In a copy of the original image, clear those pixels that don't correspond to the brain
brain_out[brain_mask == False] = (0, 0, 0)  # Set non-brain pixels to black

ShowImage('Connected Components', brain_out, 'rgb')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from ipywidgets import interact
import numpy as np
import SimpleITK as sitk
import cv2

def explore_3D_array(arr: np.ndarray, cmap: str = 'gray'):
  """
  Given a 3D array with shape (Z,X,Y) This function will create an interactive
  widget to check out all the 2D arrays with shape (X,Y) inside the 3D array. 
  The purpose of this function to visual inspect the 2D arrays in the image. 

  Args:
    arr : 3D array with shape (Z,X,Y) that represents the volume of a MRI image
    cmap : Which color map use to plot the slices in matplotlib.pyplot
  """

  def fn(SLICE):
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.imshow(arr[SLICE, :, :], cmap=cmap)

  interact(fn, SLICE=(0, arr.shape[0]-1))

files = ["2_accelerated_sagittal_mprage","3_accelerated_sagittal_mprage"]
for i in range(len(paths)):

    raw_example = path
    raw_img_path = raw_example #os.path.join(BASE_DIR, 'assets', 'raw_examples', raw_example)
    raw_img_ants = ants.image_read(raw_img_path, reorient='IAL')

    print(f'shape = {raw_img_ants.numpy().shape} -> (Z, X, Y)')

    prob_brain_mask = brain_extraction(raw_img_ants,modality="t1", verbose=True)

    brain_mask = ants.get_mask(prob_brain_mask, low_thresh=0.5) #prob_brain_mask.numpy().mean()

    masked = ants.mask_image(raw_img_ants, brain_mask)
    explore_3D_array(masked.numpy())

    out_folder =  os.path.join("./../images", files[i])

    out_filename = add_suffix_to_filename(raw_example, suffix='brainMaskByDL')
    out_path = os.path.join(out_folder, out_filename)

    brain_mask.to_file(out_path)
    masked.to_file(out_path+"_mask")
